Introduction

## People with bad or no credit have a difficult time getting a personal, home, or business loan. For folks who do want a loan, they are often preyed upon by lenders who push exorbitant fees and annual percentage rates. 

# Home Credit hopes to solve this problem by targeting their business model on customers who have bad or no credit history without using predatory lending practices. To do this, Home Credit needs to find a way to predict how capable each applicant is with loan payments. 

# For this EDA assignment, we will explore the dataset of Home Credit to get an idea of the variables we'll be working with. 

# Our project will use a classification model to categorize and predict which customers are most likely to pay off their loans. That information can then be used to supplement a risk model for approving loans to customers or for more focused marketing campaigns.

# The project deliverable will be a list of customers that would be deemed likely to pay off their loans. Any additional deliverables will be discussed and decided amongst our group and our professors. We will have a draft of our report by March 28th, 2023, with a final deliverable of our report on April 18th, 2023.

# In reviewing the number of NA variables by columns, we see a large jump in NAs once we hit the ext_source, normalized living, and credit bureau data, as well as customers with the car flag

## I am curious as to the existence of the normalized living data columns. They have a lot of mathematical information regarding a client's physical living environment. Would this information only apply to customers who are being analyzed by Home Credit? Is this information that the customer enters if they reach a certain point in a loan application process? 

## Perhaps segmenting the data to only look at normalized living data that is not NA and see if we can find any predictive patterns there would be a good route. However, this will not be covered in this assignment.

## The lack of existence of normalized living information or car flags in the data is worth noting. Does having NA  in the occupation_type mean the customer is not employed? 

## We will now look through to see if there is potential predictive power in fields with NA.

# Reviewing occupation types, people with cars older than five years, cars less than five years, and no cars at all
at %>%
  mutate(occupation_type = replace_na(occupation_type,"none"),
         own_car_age = case_when(
                                 own_car_age < 5 & own_car_age > 0~ "< 5",
                                 own_car_age > 5 ~ "> 5",
                                 own_car_age == 0 ~ "No car",
                                 TRUE ~ "No Information")) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(occupation_type, own_car_age)) %>%
 group_by(target,name,value) %>%
   summarize(n = n()) %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  mutate(total = sum(n)) %>%
  mutate(prop = n/total) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = target, values_from = prop, id_cols = c(name,value)) %>%
  mutate(diff = abs(`1` - `0`)) %>%
  arrange(desc(diff))

Exploring the Data - Bar Charts

# Since we want to predict how capable an applicant is at repaying their loan, we will explore the data and it's proportions relative to the "TARGET" variable.

# TARGET is defined as: 1 - client with payment difficulties: he/she had late payment more than X days on at least one of the first Y installments of the loan in our sample, 0 - all other cases

## NAME_CONTRACT_TYPE - Identification if loan is cash or revolving

# Number of contracts with '1' Target variable by type
ATtarget1 <- at3[at3$target == '1',]
loan_types <- table(ATtarget1$name_contract_type)
barplot(loan_types,main = "Number of contracts with '1' Target variable by type", xlab = "Contract Types", ylab =" Number of contracts", col=c("darkgreen","blue")) 

# Percentage of contracts by type
ggplot(at3, aes(x = name_contract_type, group = target)) + 
  geom_bar(aes(y = ..prop.., fill = factor(..x..)),stat = "count") +
  scale_y_continuous(labels=scales::percent, breaks = scales::pretty_breaks((n= 10))) +
  ylab("relative frequencies") + facet_grid(~target) + labs(title ="Percentage of contracts by type", x = "Target", y ="% of contracts") + 
  scale_fill_discrete(name = "Contract Type")

# Lastly - how dispersed is customer's total income?
at %>%
  mutate(amt_income_total = case_when(amt_income_total > 1 & amt_income_total < 50000 ~ "$50,000 or less",
                                      amt_income_total > 50000 & amt_income_total < 100000 ~ "Between $50,000 & 100,000",
                                      amt_income_total > 100000 & amt_income_total < 200000 ~ "Between $100,000 & 200,000",
                                      amt_income_total > 200000  ~ "More than 200,000",

                                 amt_income_total == 0 ~ "No income",
                                 TRUE ~ "No Information")) %>%
  pivot_longer(cols = c(amt_income_total)) %>%
 group_by(target,name,value) %>%
   summarize(n = n()) %>%
  group_by(name) %>%
  mutate(total = sum(n)) %>%
  mutate(prop = n/total) %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = target, values_from = prop, id_cols = c(name,value)) %>%
  mutate(diff = abs(`1` - `0`)) %>%
  arrange(desc(diff))

Ethical Consideration

# It is important that we don't make assumptions that, due to someone's gender, that it implies some predictive power for our project. 

# The gender make-up of a customer does not define why a customer may have hardship in paying off their loan.

# Looking too deeply into something like gender, sexual orientation or race as a predictive power for why someone may have difficulty paying off their loan could have us misinterpret the data and insert bias into the project output.

Results

# In reviewing our data, we have the following results:

# 1. There is predictive power in customer data that is 'NA'. For this reason, we have decided not to omit rows of data that have 'NA' values as we found predictive power in fields columns like occupation_type and flag_own_car. However, we removed the normalized housing data as there was too many NA fields in their columns, and we may not be able to extract any useful information from that data if we find any correlations.

# 2. In reviewing the number and percentage of contracts for each customer by contract type, family status, car ownership, etc., we got a better idea of the makeup of our customer base. It seems that customers with trouble paying off their loan (in majority) own realty, make on average $160,000, are married and have no children. 

# 3. We've made note to not explore gender as a predictive power for our project. Note - we have more women customers than men!

# 4. If I had more time, I would have segmented the normalized housing dataset for all non-"NA" fields. It would have been interesting to see if there were any stark differences from that dataset to the one we explored in this assignment. 

# 5. This EDA project has gotten me to feel more comfortable in using R. I have been able to create my own plots andI've pivoted and mutated many data tables. This also has given me more appreciation for performing EDA for a project - as it provides the user value in understanding the dataset before executing a project.
